 homelessness that include expanding subsidized housing to persons without disabilities and experiencing homelessness chronically, as well as taking broader measures to address vulnerabilities produced by labor markets, housing markets, and the rapid deterioration of social safety nets that often results from neoliberal globalization.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aHomeless personsxServices forzCaliforniazLos Angeles. 0aHomeless personsxServices forzJapanzTokyo. 0aHomelessnesszCaliforniazLos Angeles. 0aHomelessnesszJapanzTokyo. 0aShelters for the homelesszCaliforniazLos Angeles. 0aShelters for the homelesszJapanzTokyo. 4aAnthropology. 4aLabor History. 4aSociology & Social Science.  aHouselessness, Housing crisis, Housing market, housing lottery, international housis crisis, subsidized, vulnerable citizens.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311060674440uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978080145554440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801455544423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780801455544/original  a978-3-11-060674-4  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_PPALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles